{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"132f5ec4-065d-54c9-9f83-4903e72f947e","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field e784a012-004b-49dc-8da6-0088d52772c7 --><h2>What is it?</h2><!-- end field e784a012-004b-49dc-8da6-0088d52772c7 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 3bbdf916-3220-44c4-94c6-52848feaecf2 --><!-- begin field 0874b70f-04a2-4bda-ab9f-fbe06cb7e31c --><ul><li><strong>Shift work disorder and jet lag are both circadian rhythm sleep disorders (CRSDs).</strong><ul><li>A CRSD is a persistent or recurrent sleep disturbance that is primarily due either to changes in the circadian system or to a misalignment between a person's circadian rhythm (their 'internal clock') and exogenous or environmental factors that affect the timing or duration of sleep (such as light and social cues), due to an imposed shift in the timing of sleep. The sleep disturbance causes clinically significant distress or impairment in social or occupational functioning [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Arendt, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Wright Jr et al, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Richter, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">McKenna, 2018</a>].</li><li>This contrasts with insomnia, which describes difficulty falling asleep, disturbed sleep duration, and frequent awakening [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Richter, 2016</a>]. See the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/insomnia/\">Insomnia</a> for more information.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Shift work disorder (SWD) </strong>occurs when a person who does shift work has difficulty adjusting to different sleep/wake schedules and experiences sleep disturbance before or after the shift, and/or excessive sleepiness and fatigue during shifts. There may be associated insomnia in addition [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Morgenthaler, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Wright Jr et al, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Kecklund, 2016</a>].<ul><li>Shift work describes work time arrangements outside of conventional daytime hours, which includes fixed early morning, evening, and night work, and rotating shift work (alternating day, evening, and night shift) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Morgenthaler, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Kecklund, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Richter, 2016</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>Jet lag disorder (JLD)</strong> is a temporary CRSD related to travel across time zones in which there is a misalignment between the timing of the sleep/wake cycles generated by the person's internal circadian rhythm and that required in the new time zone (local social and environmental time cues). Associated symptoms such as insomnia or excessive daytime sleepiness occur within one to two days after travel, and may be worsened by general travel fatigue [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Morgenthaler, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Arendt, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Bin, 2019</a>].<ul><li>The rate of time zone adaptation and the type and severity of jet lag symptoms following travel varies between different people and also may vary for a given individuial between trips. People travelling over 1–3 time zones tend not to experience significant symptoms of jet lag, and adaptation is typically slower with travel towards the east [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Atkinson, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag/references/\">Arendt, 2018</a>].</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 0874b70f-04a2-4bda-ab9f-fbe06cb7e31c --><!-- end item 3bbdf916-3220-44c4-94c6-52848feaecf2 -->","topic":{"id":"3964f7a0-31e0-5fbb-acd2-28c331f8537e","topicId":"00508bc9-f2ae-4b62-92b6-6813013390e7","topicName":"Sleep disorders - shift work and jet lag","slug":"sleep-disorders-shift-work-jet-lag","lastRevised":"Last revised in November 2019","chapters":[{"id":"75b83b6f-3a17-5dc7-aaaf-e1b6b03327b4","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"a06c50c6-432a-5239-ac77-63d42196c27b","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e323be68-8cbf-5d0d-8e67-715bbd68f4fe","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"3e71c356-1580-53be-a318-f61bddebbe31","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"161f4a52-fee2-5c49-b8b5-e7e55898959d","sl